ia. Since 1995 he has been publishing poetry, articles and translations. In 2000 after completing his graduation he moved to Dubai, United Arab Emirates and founded Oxygen, an online cultural magazine in [[Arabic Language]].\n\nFrom 2005 to 2012 as a film critic, he reviewed many films from the international arena of the Arab cinema world. During this period, he also wrote for journals and magazines such as Al Akhbar, Al Hayat, Al Bayan, Alaraby, and Al Faisal,  and was also a jury member of the Al Khaleej Film Festival 2007. He founded Oxygen magazine in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0623\u0648\u0643\u0633\u062c\u064a\u0646 {{!}} \u0646\u0635\u0641 \u0634\u0647\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u062b\u0642\u0627\u0641\u064a\u0629 |url=http://o2publishing.com |website=o2publishing.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Ziad joined [[Dubai International Film Festival]] as a programmer<ref>{{cite web |title=Dubai International Film Festival picks top 100 Arab films |url=https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/dubai-international-film-festival-picks-top-100-arab-films-1.1251874 |website=gulfnews.com |language=en}}</ref> and developing manager and worked on the project Top 100 Arabic Films (DIFF).<ref>{{cite web |title=\"\u0623\u0647\u0645 100 \u0641\u064a\u0644\u0645 \u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\" \u0647\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0639\u0634\u0627\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0646\u0645\u0627 |url=https://www.emaratalyoum.com/life/cinema/2013-11-07-1.621381 |website=\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0645 |language=ar |date=7 November 2013}}</ref> Since 2016 he has been working with the [[Sharjah Art Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\u062f\u0639\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u0631\u062c\u0645\u064a\u0646 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u060c \u0645\u0634\u0631\u0648\u0639 \u0643\u0644\u0645\u0629 |url=https://www.sorbonne.ae/ar/discover/events/the-situation-of-translators-in-the-arab-world/ |website=sorbonne.ae}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mystery of Arabic cinema |url=https://www.timeoutabudhabi.com/films/features/42328-mystery-of-arabic-cinema |website=Time Out Abu Dhabi |language=en |date=2 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs a columnist, Ziad also contributes in notable news papers such as [[The New Arab]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Abdullah |first1=Ziad |title=Edward Said: The late author was just in time |url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/artsandculture/2015/2/3/edward-said-the-late-author-was-just-in-time |website=alaraby |language=en}}</ref> [[Al Akhbar (Lebanon)]],<ref>{{cite web |title=\"\u0633\u0628\u0627\u064a\u062f\u0631\u0645\u0627\u0646\" \u0644\u0646 \u064a\u0623\u062a\u064a |url=https://al-akhbar.com/Media_Tv/146164 |website=\u0627\u0644\u0623\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631 |language=ar}}</ref> [[Al-Hayat]]<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0633\u0627\u0626\u0642 \u0631\u0627\u0648\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0627\u062c \u0636\u062d\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u064a\u0651\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0646\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u062b\u064a |url=http://www.alhayat.com/article/601754/\u0633\u0627\u0626\u0642-\u0631\u0627\u0648\u064a-\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0627\u062c-\u0636\u062d\u064a\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u064a\u0629-\u0648\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0646\u0641-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u062b\u064a |website=www.alhayat.com}}</ref> and [[Emarat Al Youm]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 |first1=\u0632\u064a\u0627\u062f |title=\u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0646\u0645\u0627 \u0648\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u062a\u0635\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0627\u0631 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0632\u0645\u0646 |url=https://www.emaratalyoum.com/life/cinema/2011-03-10-1.366099 |website=\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0645 |language=ar |date=10 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\nAs a screenwriter Ziad wrote story of American educational children's television series [[Sesame Street]] and Beep (short film 2011) which was also selected for [[Oran International Arabic Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0648\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0646\u0645\u0627\u0626\u064a \u00bb.. \u062c\u0646\u0629 \u00ab \u0633\u0640\u0640\u0646\u0648\u0627\u062a |url=https://www.emaratalyoum.com/life/cinema/2011-12-18-1.445858 |website=emaratalyoum.com}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Poetry===\n* A Little Before Ink (2000) \n* Angels of Highways (2005)\n\n===Novels & short stories===\n* Bur Dubai (2008)<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0632\u064a\u0627\u062f \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647: \"\u0628\u0631 \u062f\u0628\u064a\" \u0628\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0631\u0627\u0645\u0627 \u062a\u0648\u062b\u064a\u0642\u064a\u0629 \u0639\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0634\u0631 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0623\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0645 |url=http://www.alkhaleej.ae/supplements/page/a3388088-9e1f-4e9c-ab37-9a95dd7e6c1e |website=www.alkhaleej.ae}}</ref>\n* Dynamite (2012) \n* The Strange Chronicles of The Half-Named Man (Collection of short stories 2016) \n* Dogs of Liberated Zones (Novel 2017)\n\n===Translations===\n* Burning in Water, Drowning in Flame by Charles Bukowski (2016)<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0645\u062d\u062a\u0631\u0642\u0627\u064b \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0621 \u063a\u0627\u0631\u0642\u0627\u064b \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647\u0628 |url=https://www.goodreads.com/de/book/show/30127729 |website=www.goodreads.com}}</ref>\n* Ways of Seeing by John Berger (2017)\n\n===Edited books===\n* The Color Purple, by Alice Walker (2018)\n* Possessing the Secret of Joy, by Alice Walker (2018)<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0627\u0645\u062a\u0644\u0627\u0643 \u0633\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0647\u062c\u0629 |url=http://daralmada.com/site/show/1295 |website=\u0627\u0645\u062a\u0644\u0627\u0643 \u0633\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0647\u062c\u0629}}</ref>\n* Save Me the Waltz by Zelda Fitzgerald (2018)<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0634\u0627\u0631\u0643\u0646\u064a \u0647\u0630\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0627\u0644\u0633 |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41219007 |website=www.goodreads.com}}</ref>\n* Oracle Nights by Paul Auster (2018)\n\n==Critic==\n* Cinema of Passion (Dubai International Film Festival's Top 100 Arabic Films 2016)<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vivarelli |first1=Nick |last2=Vivarelli |first2=Nick |title=Chadi Abdel Salem\u2019s \u2018The Mummy\u2019 Tops List of 100 Greatest Arab Films |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/chadi-abdel-salems-the-mummy-tops-list-of-100-greatest-arab-films-1200801556/ |website=Variety |language=en |date=6 November 2013}}</ref>\n* Islam and Laughter (2018)<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0636\u062d\u0643 - \u0646\u0648\u0627\u0636\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0627\u0637\u0631 \u0641\u064a \u0643\u0644 \u0645\u0633\u062a\u0637\u0631\u0641 \u0628\u0627\u0647\u0631 |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42825465-- |website=www.goodreads.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Syrian writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Syrian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ziad_Abdullah"}
{"title_page": "Lyle and Erik Menendez", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name              = Lyle Men\u00e9ndez\n| image             = Menendez brothers - mug shot.jpg\n| image_size        = 400px\n| alt               = \n| caption           = Mug shots of Lyle (left) and Erik Men\u00e9ndez (right)\n| birth_name        = Joseph Lyle Men\u00e9ndez\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1968|1|10}}\n| birth_place       = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| nationality       = American\n| criminal_charge   = First-degree murder, conspiracy to commit murder\n| penalty           = [[Life imprisonment|Life in prison without the possibility of parole]]\n| conviction_status = Incarcerated\n| spouse            = {{marriage|Anna Eriksson|1996|2001|reason=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|Rebecca Sneed|2003}}\n| parents           = Jos\u00e9 and Mary \"Kitty\" Men\u00e9ndez\n| motive            = Physical and alleged sexual abuse\n| conviction        = \n| partners          = Erik Men\u00e9ndez\n| comments          = \n| victims           = \n| date              = August 20, 1989\n| time              = \n| country           = United States\n| states            = [[California]]\n| locations         = [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]]\n| targets           = Jos\u00e9 and Kitty Men\u00e9ndez\n| fatalities        = 2\n| weapons           = Mossberg 12-gauge shotgun\n| apprehended       = March 8, 1990\n| imprisoned        = [[Richard J. Donovan Correctional Facility]]<ref>[https://inmatelocator.cdcr.ca.gov/Details.aspx?ID=K13758 CDCR] - State of California Inmate Locator</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name              = Erik Men\u00e9ndez\n| image             = Menendez brothers - mug shot.jpg\n| image_size        = 400px\n| alt               = \n| caption           = Mug shots of Lyle (left) and Erik Men\u00e9ndez (right)\n| birth_name        = Erik Galen Men\u00e9ndez\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1970|11|27}}\n| birth_place       = [[Blackwood, New Jersey|Blackwood]], [[New Jersey]]\n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| residence         = \n| nationality       = American \n| criminal_charge   = First-degree murder, conspiracy to commit murder\n| penalty           = [[Life imprisonment|Life in prison without the possibility of parole]]\n| conviction_status = Incarcerated\n| spouse            = {{marriage|Tammi Ruth Saccoman|1999|}}\n| parents           = Jos\u00e9 and Mary \"Kitty\" Men\u00e9ndez\n| motive            = Physical and alleged sexual abuse\n| partners          = Lyle Men\u00e9ndez\n| victims           = \n| date              = August 20, 1989\n| time              = \n| country           = United States\n| states            = [[California]]\n| locations         = [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]]\n| targets           = Jos\u00e9 and Kitty Men\u00e9ndez\n| fatalities        = 2\n| weapons           = Mossberg 12-gauge shotgun\n| apprehended       = March 11, 1990\n| imprisoned        = [[Richard J. Donovan Correctional Facility]]<ref>[https://inmatelocator.cdcr.ca.gov/Details.aspx?ID=K14101 CDCR] - State of California Inmate Locator</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Lyle Men\u00e9ndez''' (born January 10, 1968) and '''Erik Galen Men\u00e9ndez''' (born November 27, 1970) are American brothers who were convicted in 1996 for the 1989 shotgun murders of their wealthy parents, entertainment executive Jos\u00e9 Men\u00e9ndez and his wife Mary (\"Kitty\"). Although the brothers were not considered suspects at first, suspicions about their involvement arose when they began to spend money lavishly after the murders. During the trial, the brothers alleged that they committed the murders because of years of [[sexual abuse|sexual]] and [[emotional abuse]] that they suffered at the hands of their parents, particularly their father. They were first tried separately, with one jury for each brother. Both juries deadlocked, which resulted in a mistrial. For the second trial, they were tried together by the same jury, which found them guilty, and as a result, they were sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole.\n\n==Background==\nLyle and Erik's father, Jos\u00e9 Enrique Men\u00e9ndez, was born on May 6, 1944 in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]. At age 16, he moved to the [[United States]] after the [[Cuban Revolution]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0580036/bio|title=Jose Menendez|website=IMDb|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> Jos\u00e9 attended [[Southern Illinois University]], where he met Mary Louise \"Kitty\" Andersen (1941\u20131989). They married in 1963 and moved to [[New York City]], where Jos\u00e9 earned an accounting degree from [[Queens College, City University of New York|Queens College]].<ref name=johnson>{{Cite news | last1=Johnson | first1=John | last2=Soble | first2=Ronald L. | title=The Menendez Brothers: Jose Menendez Gave His Sons Everything. Maybe Even a Motive for Murder.|url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/1990-07-22/magazine/tm-930_1_jose-menendez|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 22, 1990|page=3}}</ref> The couple's first son, Joseph Lyle Men\u00e9ndez, who goes by his middle name, was born on January 10, 1968.<ref name=\"Crime Library\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/famous/menendez/life_5.html | title=The Men\u00e9ndez Brothers | last=Pergament | first=Rachel | website=[[Crime Library]] | date= | accessdate=November 18, 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102021701/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/famous/menendez/life_5.html | archivedate=November 2, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\nKitty quit her teaching job after Lyle was born, and the family moved to [[New Jersey]], where Erik was born on November 27, 1970 in [[Gloucester Township, New Jersey|Gloucester Township]].<ref name=biography>{{cite web|title=Erik Men\u00e9ndez Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/erik-menendez-10367586#life-behind-bars&|website=biography.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1375835/bio|title=Kitty Menendez|website=IMDb|access-date=December 7, 2017}}</ref>{{r|biography}} In New Jersey, the family lived in [[Hopewell Township, Mercer County, New Jersey]] and both brothers attended [[Princeton Day School]].<ref name=johnson/> In 1986, Jos\u00e9's career as a corporate executive took the family to [[Calabasas, California|Calabasas]], [[California]].<ref name=biography/><ref name=johnson/> The following year, Erik began attending high school in Calabasas, where he earned average grades, but had a remarkable talent for [[tennis]], as he ranked 44th in the nation for 18-and-under players.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://communitynews.org/2017/09/26/look-back-at-the-story-and-coverage-of-the-menendez-murders/|title=A look back at the story \u2013 and coverage \u2013 of the Menendez murders|date=September 26, 2017|work=Community News|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Lyle enrolled at [[Princeton University]], but during his freshman year, he was placed on academic probation for poor grades and attendance, and was eventually suspended for a year after being accused of plagiarism.\n\n== Crimes ==\nOn the evening of August 20, 1989, Jos\u00e9 and Kitty were sitting on a couch in the den of their house in [[Beverly Hills]] when Lyle and Erik entered the den carrying shotguns.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/lyle-menendez-speaks-from-prison-27-years-after-killing-parents-w458981|title=Lyle Menendez Finally Speaks From Prison, 27 Years After Killing His Parents|magazine=[[Us Weekly]]|date=January 4, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Jos\u00e9 was shot in the back of the head with a Mossberg 12-gauge shotgun.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.biography.com/news/menendez-brothers-murder-case-facts|title=True Crime Revisited: The Menendez Brothers Case|work=Biography.com|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> Kitty was awakened by the shots and got up from the couch. She was shot in the leg while running toward the hallway, causing her to slip on her own blood and fall, and was then shot several times in the arm, chest, and face, leaving her unrecognizable. Both Jos\u00e9 and Kitty were also shot in the kneecaps in an attempt to make the murders appear connected to organized crime.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Natalie|last=Finn|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/845635/we-can-t-forget-just-how-insane-the-menendez-brothers-murder-case-was-in-its-day-or-in-any-day|title=Remembering the Insanity of the Menendez Brothers Murder Case|work=[[E! Online]]|date=April 26, 2018|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://people.com/archive/cover-story-a-beverly-hills-paradise-lost-vol-33-no-12/\n| title      = A Beverly Hills Paradise Lost\n| work       = [[People (magazine)|People]]\n| first     = Joseph \n| last      = Poindexter\n| date       = March 26, 1990\n| accessdate = February 8, 2017\n}}</ref>\n\nWhen they returned home later that night, Lyle called 9-1-1 and shouted \"Someone killed my parents!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t3PA37erNYw|title=Why the Menendez Brothers Say They Killed Their Parents: Part 1|access-date=2017-01-06|language=en}}</ref> When the police came, the brothers told them that they went to the theater to see the movie ''[[Batman (1989 film)|Batman]]'' and then to the annual \"Taste of L.A.\" festival at the [[Santa Monica Civic Auditorium]] during the murders, but they did not order the brothers to go through gunshot residue tests to find out whether they had recently used a firearm<ref name=\"vf\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/archive/1990/10/dunne199010 |title=Nightmare on Elm Drive |first=Dominick |last=Dunne |authorlink=Dominick Dunne |date=October 1990 |magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |quote=Beverly Hills police claimed to have been suspicious of the Men\u00e9ndez brothers from the beginning.... But there was no proof &ndash; nothing to go on &ndash; merely gut reactions.}}</ref> since a lack of evidence prevented them from looking into the brothers more thoroughly. In the months after the murders, the brothers began to spend money lavishly, adding to suspicions that they were somehow involved in the murders of their parents.<ref name=\"vf\"/> Lyle bought a Rolex watch, a [[Porsche 964|Porsche Carrera]], and Chuck's Spring Street Cafe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princetonsrestaurants.com/restaurant/Princeton-NJ/Chuck%27s-Spring-Street-Cafe |title=Chuck's Spring Street Cafe in Princeton, NJ  |publisher=Princetonsrestaurants.com |date= |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref> a [[Buffalo wing]] restaurant in [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]], [[New Jersey]] while Erik hired a full-time tennis coach and competed in a series of tournaments in [[Israel]]. They eventually left the family mansion unoccupied, as they decided to live in adjoining condos in nearby [[Marina del Rey, California|Marina del Rey]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.refinery29.com/2017/09/174002/menendez-brothers-money-spent-shopping-law-and-order|title=Here's How Much The Menendez Brothers Spent On Their Spree|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref> They also drove around [[Los Angeles]] in their deceased mother's [[Mercedes-Benz SL-Class|Mercedes-Benz SL]] convertible, dined expensively, and went on overseas trips to the [[Caribbean]] and [[London]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/883055/lost-in-l-a-this-menendez-brothers-murder-map-will-help-you-put-the-crazy-sprawling-story-into-perspective|title=This Menendez Brothers Murder Map Puts the Crazy Story in Perspective|work=E! Online|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> It is believed that they spent somewhere around $700,000 during the time period between the murders and their arrests.<ref name=\"vf\"/>\n\nDuring the early stages of the investigation, the police tried to narrow their search down to people who would have had motives to kill Jos\u00e9 and Kitty. One of these people included a pornography distributor named Noel C. Bloom,<ref name=johnson/> but he was found to have had no involvement and was quickly cleared. They also investigated potential mob leads, but nothing came out of those leads. As the investigation continued, the police believed that the brothers were most likely the culprits since they had obvious financial motives and were spending lots of money just after the murders. In an attempt to get a confession from Erik, the police got Craig Cignarelli, one of Erik's close friends from high school and tennis buddy, to wear a wire while having lunch with him at a local beachfront restaurant.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/1993/10/dunne199310|title=The Menendez Murder Trial|last=Dunne|first=Dominick|authorlink=Dominick Dunne|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|language=en|date=September 15, 2008|access-date=May 10, 2019}}</ref> When Craig asked Erik if he killed his parents, Erik initially said no, but eventually confessed to doing so to his [[psychologist]] Jerome Oziel. After Lyle threatened him, Oziel told his mistress Judalon Smyth about the murders, and she told the police about the brothers' involvement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-11-16/local/me-57401_1_stormy-affair|title=Menendez Therapist's Ex-Lover Testifies : Trial: She says Oziel wanted the brothers to confess on tape so he could 'control' them. Calls that the woman secretly recorded of the stormy affair are also played in court.|last=Abrahamson|first=Alan|date=November 16, 1993|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> Lyle was arrested on March 8, 1990, and Erik turned himself in three days later after returning to Los Angeles from Israel. Both were held without bail and separated from each other.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/crime-files/menendez-brothers/arrest|title=The Arrest|date=June 29, 2017|work=Crime + Investigation|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref> In August 1990, Judge James Albrecht stated that tapes of the conversations between Erik and Oziel were admissible since Lyle violated [[physician\u2013patient privilege|doctor\u2013patient privilege]] by threatening Oziel. However, since that ruling was appealed, the proceedings were delayed for two years. The Supreme Court of California then stated in August 1992 that most of these tapes were admissible except the one of Erik discussing the murders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/california/supreme-court/4th/3/435.html|title=Menendez v. Superior Court (People) (1992)|work=Justia Law|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref> After that decision, a Los Angeles County grand jury issued indictments in December 1992, charging the brothers with the murders of their parents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-12-30/local/me-2458_1_grand-jury|title=Menendez Brothers Plead Innocent in Killings : Court: Grand jury indictment means trial in the deaths of their parents could begin in March.|last=McMilla|first=Penelope|date=December 30, 1992|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\n==Trials==\nThe case became a national sensation when [[Court TV]] broadcast the trial in 1993.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/article/1993/11/12/confessions-court-tv-addict/|title=Confessions of a Court TV Addict|last=Cagle|first=Jess|date=November 12, 1993|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=June 9, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> Their defense lawyer [[Leslie Abramson]] became known for her theory that the brothers were driven to murder by a lifetime of [[child abuse|abuse]] at the hands of their parents, especially [[abuse defense|sexual abuse]] at the hands of their father, who was described as a cruel [[perfectionism (psychology)|perfectionist]] and [[pedophilia|pedophile]]. Meanwhile, their mother was described as a selfish, mentally unstable [[alcoholism|alcoholic]] and [[drug addict]] who encouraged her husband's abuses and was also sometimes violent towards them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/notorious_murders/famous/menendez/trial_16.html | title=The Men\u00e9ndez Brothers |accessdate=December 3, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012213355/http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/notorious_murders/famous/menendez/trial_16.html |archivedate=October 12, 2012}}</ref> The trial ended with two deadlocked juries as a result, and Los Angeles County District Attorney Gil Garcetti announced immediately that the brothers would be retried. The second trial was somewhat less publicized, partly because Judge Stanley Weisberg did not allow cameras in the courtroom.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chiasson|first1=Lloyd|title=The Press on Trial: Crimes and Trials as Media Events|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|location=Westport, Connecticut|date=1997|page=200|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qdGpzU_qWA0C&pg=PA200&lpg=PA200&dq=stanley+weisberg+refuse+cameras+menendez#v=onepage&q=stanley%20weisberg%20refuse%20cameras%20menendez&f=false|accessdate=June 3, 2015|isbn=9780313300226}}</ref> Also during the second trial, Weisberg did not allow much defense testimony about the sexual abuse claims<ref>{{cite web|title=Legal Loophole Could Give Murderous Brothers Erik And Lyle Menendez Chance For New Trial|url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/11/17/legal-loophole-could-give-murderous-brothers-erik-lyle-menendez-chance-for-new-trial|website=[[CBS Los Angeles]]|date=November 17, 2016}}</ref> and did not allow the jury to vote on manslaughter charges instead of murder charges.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tammi Menendez on Loving Erik|url=http://abcnews.go.com/2020/story?id=123804&page=1|website=[[ABC News]]|date=September 27, 2002}}</ref>\n\nBoth brothers were eventually convicted of two counts of first-degree murder and conspiracy to commit murder, and in the penalty phase of the trial, they were sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole. The jury said that the abuse defense was not a factor in its deliberations, but chose not to impose the death penalty because both brothers had no criminal record or history of violence prior to the murders of their parents. However, unlike the juries in the previous trials, the jury in the penalty phase rejected the defense's theory that the brothers had killed their parents out of fear, as it is believed that they committed the murders in order to inherit their father's wealth.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Abrahamson|first1=Alan|title=Little Remains of Men\u00e9ndez Estate, Records Show : Courts: Inheritance of $14.5&nbsp;million was lost to taxes, lawyers' fees and inflated real estate appraisals, probate files reveal|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-04-03/local/me-41704_1_real-estate-appraisals|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 3, 1994}}</ref> During the penalty phase of the trial, Abramson apparently told a defense witness named William Vicary to edit his notes, but the district attorney's office decided not to conduct a criminal investigation.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/12/us/menendez-lawyer-won-t-face-investigation.html |title = Menendez Lawyer Won't Face Investigation | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = October 12, 1997 | accessdate = May 26, 2014 }}</ref> Both brothers also filed motions for a mistrial, claiming that they had suffered irreversible damage in the penalty phase as a result of possible misconduct and ineffective representation by Abramson. On July 2, 1996, Weisberg sentenced the brothers to life in prison without the possibility of parole, and also sentenced them to consecutive sentences for the murders and the charges of conspiracy to commit murder.\n\n==Incarceration==\nJust like their pretrial detention, the California Department of Corrections separated the brothers and sent them to different prisons. Since they were considered to be maximum-security inmates, they were segregated from other prisoners. They remained in separate prisons until February 2018 when Lyle was moved from [[Mule Creek State Prison]] in Northern California to the [[Richard J. Donovan Correctional Facility]]<ref>[https://inmatelocator.cdcr.ca.gov/Details.aspx?ID=K14101 State of California Inmate Locator] \u2013 CDCR</ref> in San Diego County, but were housed in separate units until April 4, 2018 when Lyle was moved to the same housing unit as Erik, reuniting them for the first time since they began serving their sentences nearly 22 years earlier. Both brothers burst into tears and hugged each other at their first meeting in the housing unit. The unit where the brothers are housed is reserved for inmates who agree to participate in educational and other rehabilitation programs without creating disruptions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Menendez brothers who killed parents reunited in California prison|url=http://freep.mi.newsmemory.com/?token=62b248b84fa909472d7737ac1bb2b800&cnum=7361672&fod=1111111STD&selDate=20180407&licenseType=paid_subscriber&|accessdate=April 7, 2018|issue=|publisher=Detroit Free Press|date=April 7, 2018|page=3C|language=English|format=newspaper}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/parent-killing-menendez-brothers-burst-tears-reuniting-article-1.3918859|title=Parent-killing Menendez brothers 'burst into tears' upon reuniting for first time since sentencing|author=Sommerfeldt, Chris|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=2018-04-06|accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Menendez brothers convicted of killing parents reunite in jail|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-43663451|website=bbc.com|date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Appeals==\nOn February 27, 1998, the California Court of Appeal upheld their murder convictions, and on May 28, 1998, the Supreme Court of California upheld their murder convictions and sentences without any Supreme Court judges reviewing the case.<ref name=\"Crime Library\"/> Both brothers filed ''[[habeas corpus]]'' petitions with the Supreme Court of California, which were denied in 1999. Having exhausted their appeal remedies in state court, they filed separate habeas corpus petitions in the United States District Court. On March 4, 2003, a magistrate judge recommended the denial of the petitions,{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} and the district court adopted the recommendation. They then decided to appeal to the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit. On September 7, 2005, a three-judge panel denied both their habeas corpus petitions,<ref>{{cite web|title=United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit |url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2005/09/07/0355863.pdf|website=uscourts.gov|accessdate=June 8, 2017}}</ref> although Judge Alex Kozinski stated that the trial judge changed many of his rulings during the two trials.<ref>{{cite web|title=Law Offices of Cliff Gardner|url=http://www.cliffgardner.com/resources/menendez.mp3|website=cliffgardner.com/index.php|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Marriages and interviews in prison==\nOn July 2, 1996, Lyle married Anna Eriksson at a ceremony attended by Abramson and his aunt Marta Men\u00e9ndez, which was presided over by Judge Nancy Brown, but they divorced on April 1, 2001<ref name=\"Crime Library\" /> after Eriksson discovered that Lyle was allegedly cheating on her with another woman. In November 2003, Lyle married Rebecca Sneed at a ceremony in a supermax prison visiting area of [[Mule Creek State Prison]], and they knew each other for around ten years before their engagement.<ref>{{cite web|first=Dan|last=Abrams|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/12134256|title=Should single guys trade their pinstripes for prison stripes?|website=NBC News|date=January 18, 2006|accessdate=September 2, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/3540836|title=Parent killer Men\u00e9ndez marries in Calif. prison|website=NBC News|date=November 23, 2003|accessdate=September 2, 2008}}</ref> On June 12, 1999, Erik married Tammi Ruth Saccoman at [[Folsom State Prison]] in a prison waiting room. Tammi later stated: \"Our wedding cake was a Twinkie. We improvised. It was a wonderful ceremony until I had to leave. That was a very lonely night.\"<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine|first=Bill|last=Hewitt|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20144791,00.html|title=Life & Love Behind Bars|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=November 7, 2005|volume=64|number=19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://edition.cnn.com/US/9906/16/menendez/| title=Convicted murderer Erik Men\u00e9ndez marries in prison | website=[[CNN]]|date= June 16, 1999 | accessdate =July 19, 2008}}</ref> In an October 2005 interview with [[ABC News]], she described her relationship with Erik as \"something that I've dreamed about for a long time. And it's just something very special that I never thought that I would ever have.\"<ref name=ABC1>{{cite news | url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=1255023| title=Erik Men\u00e9ndez's Life Behind Bars| website= [[ABC News]] |date= October 25, 2005 | accessdate =July 19, 2008}}</ref> In 2005, Tammi self-published a book titled ''They Said We'd Never Make It \u2013 My Life With Erik Men\u00e9ndez'', but she said on ''[[Larry King Live]]'' that Erik also \"did a lot of editing on the book.\"<ref name=\"cnn_tammy\">{{cite news | accessdate=2015-06-13 | date= December 20, 2005 | publisher=CNN | title=Interview With Tammi Men\u00e9ndez | url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0512/20/lkl.01.html}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2005 interview with ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine, she stated: \"Not having sex in my life is difficult, but it's not a problem for me. I have to be emotionally attached, and I'm emotionally attached to Erik.... My family does not understand. When it started to get serious, some of them just threw up their hands.\" Tammi also stated that she and her daughter drive the {{convert|150|mi}} every weekend to visit Erik, and that her daughter refers to him as her \"Earth Dad.\"<ref name=\"people\" /> Despite his life sentence, Erik stated: \"Tammi is what gets me through. I can't think about the sentence. When I do, I do it with a great sadness and a primal fear. I break into a cold sweat. It's so frightening I just haven't come to terms with it.\"<ref name=\"people\" /> In 2010, [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] released a documentary about Tammi titled ''Mrs. Men\u00e9ndez''.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|title=Men\u00e9ndez brothers convicted in parents' murder 16 years ago|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/03/menendez-brothers.html|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 20, 2012}}</ref> In late 2017, A&E aired a five-part documentary titled ''The Menendez Murders: Erik Tells All'' in which Erik, via telephone, recalls the murders and the aftermath. The series also shows never-before-seen photos and new interviews with prosecutors, law enforcement, close family and friends, and medical experts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/menendez-murders-erik-tells-all/listings/|title=The Menendez Murders: Erik Tells All|website=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=November 30, 2017|accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe ''[[Law & Order]]'' Season 1 episode \"[[Law & Order (season_1)#ep19|The Serpent's Tooth]]\" is loosely based on the The Menendez Brothers case. The Menendez brothers were also featured in a 2017 documentary titled ''Truth and Lies: The Men\u00e9ndez Brothers \u2013 American Sons, American Murderers'' on ABC, as well as on an episode of ''[[Snapped]]'' in 2016. The murders are the subjects of multiple docu-dramas, including the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] movie ''[[Menendez: Blood Brothers]]'' (2017), and the television films ''[[Menendez: A Killing in Beverly Hills]]'' on CBS and ''Honor Thy Father and Mother: The True Story of the Menendez Murders'' on Fox, both in 1994. The media hype surrounding the first trial was parodied in the 1996 dark comedy film ''[[The Cable Guy]]''. The Men\u00e9ndez brothers were subjects of the weekly satire podcast ''[[The Last Podcast on the Left]]'' in 2016 and were depicted in the film ''[[Natural Born Killers]]''. Their story was also featured in an episode of ''Barbara Walters Presents: American Scandals'' titled \"Menendez Brothers: The Bad Sons\" and in a documentary series from Court TV, now TruTV, in an episode titled ''Mugshots: Menendez Brothers \u2013 Blood Brothers'' in 2000 at ''[[FilmRise]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mugshots: Menendez Brothers|url=http://filmrise.com/mugshots-menendez-brothers/|website=FilmRise|accessdate=November 8, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mugshots (TV Series 2000)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0320080/episodes?ref_=tt_ov_epl|website=imdb.com|accessdate=October 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Menendez Brothers \u2013 Blood Brothers: Ellen Goosenberg Kent|url=https://www.amazon.com/Mugshots-Menendez-Brothers-Blood/dp/B00D0XOBSQ|website=www.amazon.com|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Law & Order True Crime|Law & Order True Crime: The Men\u00e9ndez Murders]]'' premiered on NBC in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/09/26/entertainment/law-and-order-true-crime-menendez-murders-review/index.html|title='Law & Order True Crime: The Menendez Murders' review|last=Lowry|first=Brian|date=September 26, 2017|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> In addition, Season 4, Episode One of ''[[Jake and the Fatman]]'', entitled '''God Bless the Child''' appears to be based upon these killings, with the son and daughter of a shipping magnate kill him and their stepmother, so as not to lose their inheritance.\n\n[[HLN (TV network)|HLN]] launched the new series [[HLN (TV network)#Programming|''How it Really Happened with Hill Harper'']], with an episode featuring the Men\u00e9ndez brothers story. The episode is titled \"The Men\u00e9ndez Brothers: Murder in Beverly Hills\",  and it ends with a telephone interview of Lyle from jail with [[Chris Cuomo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=How It Really Happened with Hill Harper {{!}} The Menendez Brothers: Murder in Beverly Hills|url=http://www.cnn.com/interactive/2017/hln/how-it-really-happened/the-menendez-brothers/|accessdate=October 14, 2017|work=HLN|publisher=Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.|date=January 27, 2017}}</ref> The Menendez brothers are believed to be in the background of the [[1990\u201391 NBA season|1990\u201391]] NBA Hoops [[Mark Jackson (basketball)|Mark Jackson]] basketball card in which the [[New York Knicks]] point guard is seen making a bounce pass and they appear to be sitting courtside behind Jackson.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Skiver |first1=Kevin |title=Menendez brothers appear in background of Mark Jackson basketball card |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/menendez-brothers-appear-in-background-of-mark-jackson-basketball-card/ |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |publisher=CBS Sports |date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, [[eBay]] began pulling auctions in which they are mentioned in the listing. The New York Knicks had played 28 games during the period when the Menendez brothers went on a spending spree after the murders of their parents. Some eBay sellers have continued to sell the card and have also altered the images accompanying the listing so that the men purported to be the Menendez brothers are neither mentioned in the listing nor seen in photos of the card accompanying the listing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=D'Angelo |first1=Bob |title=Double Take: Infamous Menendez Brothers and the 1990\u201391 Hoops Mark Jackson |url=https://www.sportscollectorsdaily.com/double-take-infamous-menendez-brothers-and-the-1990-91-hoops-mark-jackson/ |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |publisher=Sports Collectors Daily |date=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Parricide]]\n* [[Stacey Lannert]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n===Books===\n* Davis, Don (1994) ''Bad Blood: The Shocking True Story Behind the Men\u00e9ndez Killings'' St. Martin, New York, {{ISBN|0-312-95334-8}}\n* Men\u00e9ndez, Lyle; Novelli, Norma; Walker, Mike; and Spreckels, Judith (1995) ''The Private Diary of Lyle Men\u00e9ndez: In His Own Words!'' Dove Books, Beverly Hills, California, {{ISBN|0-7871-0474-4}}\n* Men\u00e9ndez, Tammi (2005) ''They Said We'd Never Make It: My Life With Erik Men\u00e9ndez'' NewGalen Publishing, Santa Clarita, California, {{ISBN|0-9768744-0-7}}\n* Soble, Ronald L. and Johnson, John (1994) ''Blood Brothers: The Inside Story of the Men\u00e9ndez Murders'' Onyx, New York, {{ISBN|0-451-40547-1}}\n* Thornton, Hazel; Wrightsman, Lawrence S.; Posey, Amy J. and Scheflin, Alan W. (1995) ''Hung Jury: The Diary of a Men\u00e9ndez Juror'' Temple University Press, Philadelphia; new \"20 Years Later\" edition updated with new material, Graymalkin Media (2017) {{ISBN|978-1631681622}}\n* Rand, Robert (2018) ''The Menendez Murders: The Shocking Untold Story of the Menendez Family and the Killings that Stunned the Nation'' BenBella Books {{ISBN|978-1946885265}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/archive/1990/10/dunne199010 Nightmare on Elm Drive] by [[Dominick Dunne]]. ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', October 1990\n* [http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/archive/1996/06/dunne199606 Three Faces of Evil] by [[Dominick Dunne]]. ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', June 1996\n* [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/10573267 Wife of Erik Men\u00e9ndez talks about relationship] at MSNBC TV, December 22, 2005\n* [http://abcnews.go.com/2020/Story?id=123804&page=1 Tammi Men\u00e9ndez on Loving Erik] at [[ABC News]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061006112240/http://www.courttv.com/trials/menendez/ Men\u00e9ndez Brothers] at Court TV (now [[TruTV]])\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061107093811/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/famous/menendez/index_1.html Men\u00e9ndez Brothers] at [[Crime Library]]\n* [http://www.thesmokinggun.com/mugshots/menendezmug1.html Mug shots of the brothers] on [[The Smoking Gun]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20000818085030/http://www.courttv.com/casefiles/menendez/transcripts/ archived trial transcripts] from Court TV\n* {{LCAuth|n94062388|Lyle Men\u00e9ndez|1|}}\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-n94-062388|Lyle Men\u00e9ndez}}\n* [http://lccn.loc.gov/n94062384 Erik Men\u00e9ndez] at LC Authorities, with no records<!-- 2015-04-28 -->\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-n94-062384|Erik Men\u00e9ndez}}\n\n<!-- some categories individual to one person, e.g., birth and death year or living person are under the redirect for that person -->\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Men\u00e9ndez, Lyle and Erik}}\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:1989 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:People from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Criminal duos]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Parricides]]\n[[Category:American prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:People from Hopewell Township, Mercer County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Princeton, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Crime in California]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of California]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by California]]\n[[Category:American murderers]]\n[[Category:Male murderers]]\n[[Category:People from Gloucester Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by California]]\n[[Category:Sibling duos]]\n[[Category:Princeton Day School alumni]]\n[[Category:Criminals from California]]\n[[Category:Criminals from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name              = Lyle Men\u00e9ndez\n| image             = Menendez brothers - mug shot.jpg\n| image_size        = 400px\n| alt               = \n| caption           = Mug shots of Lyle (left) and Erik Men\u00e9ndez (right)\n| birth_name        = Joseph Lyle Men\u00e9ndez\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1968|1|10}}\n| birth_place       = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| nationality       = American\n| criminal_charge   = First-degree murder, conspiracy to commit murder\n| penalty           = [[Life imprisonment|Life in prison without the possibility of parole]]\n| conviction_status = Incarcerated\n| spouse            = {{marriage|Anna Eriksson|1996|2001|reason=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|Rebecca Sneed|2003}}\n| parents           = Jos\u00e9 and Mary \"Kitty\" Men\u00e9ndez\n| motive            = Physical and alleged sexual abuse\n| conviction        = \n| partners          = Erik Men\u00e9ndez\n| comments          = \n| victims           = \n| date              = August 20, 1989\n| time              = \n| country           = United States\n| states            = [[California]]\n| locations         = [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]]\n| targets           = Jos\u00e9 and Kitty Men\u00e9ndez\n| fatalities        = 2\n| weapons           = Mossberg 12-gauge shotgun\n| apprehended       = March 8, 1990\n| imprisoned        = [[Richard J. Donovan Correctional Facility]]<ref>[https://inmatelocator.cdcr.ca.gov/Details.aspx?ID=K13758 CDCR] - State of California Inmate Locator</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name              = Erik Men\u00e9ndez\n| image             = Menendez brothers - mug shot.jpg\n| image_size        = 400px\n| alt               = \n| caption           = Mug shots of Lyle (left) and Erik Men\u00e9ndez (right)\n| birth_name        = Erik Galen Men\u00e9ndez\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1970|11|27}}\n| birth_place       = [[Blackwood, New Jersey|Blackwood]], [[New Jersey]]\n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| residence         = \n| nationality       = American \n| criminal_charge   = First-degree murder, conspiracy to commit murder\n| penalty           = [[Life imprisonment|Life in prison without the possibility of parole]]\n| conviction_status = Incarcerated\n| spouse            = {{marriage|Tammi Ruth Saccoman|1999|}}\n| parents           = Jos\u00e9 and Mary \"Kitty\" Men\u00e9ndez\n| motive            = Physical and alleged sexual abuse\n| partners          = Lyle Men\u00e9ndez\n| victims           = \n| date              = August 20, 1989\n| time              = \n| country           = United States\n| states            = [[California]]\n| locations         = [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]]\n| targets           = Jos\u00e9 and Kitty Men\u00e9ndez\n| fatalities        = 2\n| weapons           = Mossberg 12-gauge shotgun\n| apprehended       = March 11, 1990\n| imprisoned        = [[Richard J. Donovan Correctional Facility]]<ref>[https://inmatelocator.cdcr.ca.gov/Details.aspx?ID=K14101 CDCR] - State of California Inmate Locator</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Lyle Men\u00e9ndez''' (born January 10, 1968) and '''Erik Galen Men\u00e9ndez''' (born November 27, 1970) are American brothers who were convicted in 1996 for the 1989 shotgun murders of their wealthy parents, entertainment executive Jos\u00e9 Men\u00e9ndez and his wife Mary (\"Kitty\"). Although the brothers were not considered suspects at first, suspicions about their involvement arose when they began to spend money lavishly after the murders. During the trial, the brothers alleged that they committed the murders because of years of [[sexual abuse|sexual]] and [[emotional abuse]] that they suffered at the hands of their parents, particularly their father. They were first tried separately, with one jury for each brother. Both juries deadlocked, which resulted in a mistrial. For the second trial, they were tried together by the same jury, which found them guilty, and as a result, they were sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole.\n\n==Background==\nLyle and Erik's father, Jos\u00e9 Enrique Men\u00e9ndez, was born on May 6, 1944 in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]. At age 16, he moved to the [[United States]] after the [[Cuban Revolution]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0580036/bio|title=Jose Menendez|website=IMDb|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> Jos\u00e9 attended [[Southern Illinois University]], where he met Mary Louise \"Kitty\" Andersen (1941\u20131989). They married in 1963 and moved to [[New York City]], where Jos\u00e9 earned an accounting degree from [[Queens College, City University of New York|Queens College]].<ref name=johnson>{{Cite news | last1=Johnson | first1=John | last2=Soble | first2=Ronald L. | title=The Menendez Brothers: Jose Menendez Gave His Sons Everything. Maybe Even a Motive for Murder.|url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/1990-07-22/magazine/tm-930_1_jose-menendez|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 22, 1990|page=3}}</ref> The couple's first son, Joseph Lyle Men\u00e9ndez, who goes by his middle name, was born on January 10, 1968.<ref name=\"Crime Library\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/famous/menendez/life_5.html | title=The Men\u00e9ndez Brothers | last=Pergament | first=Rachel | website=[[Crime Library]] | date= | accessdate=November 18, 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102021701/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/famous/menendez/life_5.html | archivedate=November 2, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\nKitty quit her teaching job after Lyle was born, and the family moved to [[New Jersey]], where Erik was born on November 27, 1970 in [[Gloucester Township, New Jersey|Gloucester Township]].<ref name=biography>{{cite web|title=Erik Men\u00e9ndez Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/erik-menendez-10367586#life-behind-bars&|website=biography.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1375835/bio|title=Kitty Menendez|website=IMDb|access-date=December 7, 2017}}</ref>{{r|biography}} In New Jersey, the family lived in [[Hopewell Township, Mercer County, New Jersey]] and both brothers attended [[Princeton Day School]].<ref name=johnson/> In 1986, Jos\u00e9's career as a corporate executive took the family to [[Calabasas, California|Calabasas]], [[California]].<ref name=biography/><ref name=johnson/> The following year, Erik began attending high school in Calabasas, where he earned average grades, but had a remarkable talent for [[tennis]], as he ranked 44th in the nation for 18-and-under players.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://communitynews.org/2017/09/26/look-back-at-the-story-and-coverage-of-the-menendez-murders/|title=A look back at the story \u2013 and coverage \u2013 of the Menendez murders|date=September 26, 2017|work=Community News|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Lyle enrolled at [[Princeton University]], but during his freshman year, he was placed on academic probation for poor grades and attendance, and was eventually suspended for a year after being accused of plagiarism.\n\n== Crimes ==\nOn the evening of August 20, 1989, Jos\u00e9 and Kitty were sitting on a couch in the den of their house in [[Beverly Hills]] when Lyle and Erik entered the den carrying shotguns.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/lyle-menendez-speaks-from-prison-27-years-after-killing-parents-w458981|title=Lyle Menendez Finally Speaks From Prison, 27 Years After Killing His Parents|magazine=[[Us Weekly]]|date=January 4, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Jos\u00e9 was shot in the back of the head with a Mossberg 12-gauge shotgun.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.biography.com/news/menendez-brothers-murder-case-facts|title=True Crime Revisited: The Menendez Brothers Case|work=Biography.com|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> Kitty was awakened by the shots and got up from the couch. She was shot in the leg while running toward the hallway, causing her to slip on her own blood and fall, and was then shot several times in the arm, chest, and face, leaving her unrecognizable. Both Jos\u00e9 and Kitty were also shot in the kneecaps in an attempt to make the murders appear connected to organized crime.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Natalie|last=Finn|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/845635/we-can-t-forget-just-how-insane-the-menendez-brothers-murder-case-was-in-its-day-or-in-any-day|title=Remembering the Insanity of the Menendez Brothers Murder Case|work=[[E! Online]]|date=April 26, 2018|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://people.com/archive/cover-story-a-beverly-hills-paradise-lost-vol-33-no-12/\n| title      = A Beverly Hills Paradise Lost\n| work       = [[People (magazine)|People]]\n| first     = Joseph \n| last      = Poindexter\n| date       = March 26, 1990\n| accessdate = February 8, 2017\n}}</ref>\n\nWhen they returned home later that night, Lyle called 9-1-1 and shouted \"Someone killed my parents!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t3PA37erNYw|title=Why the Menendez Brothers Say They Killed Their Parents: Part 1|access-date=2017-01-06|language=en}}</ref> When the police came, the brothers told them that they went to the theater to see the movie ''[[Batman (1989 film)|Batman]]'' and then to the annual \"Taste of L.A.\" festival at the [[Santa Monica Civic Auditorium]] during the murders, but they did not order the brothers to go through gunshot residue tests to find out whether they had recently used a firearm<ref name=\"vf\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/archive/1990/10/dunne199010 |title=Nightmare on Elm Drive |first=Dominick |last=Dunne |authorlink=Dominick Dunne |date=October 1990 |magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |quote=Beverly Hills police claimed to have been suspicious of the Men\u00e9ndez brothers from the beginning.... But there was no proof &ndash; nothing to go on &ndash; merely gut reactions.}}</ref> since a lack of evidence prevented them from looking into the brothers more thoroughly. In the months after the murders, the brothers began to spend money lavishly, adding to suspicions that they were somehow involved in the murders of their parents.<ref name=\"vf\"/> Lyle bought a Rolex watch, a [[Porsche 964|Porsche Carrera]], and Chuck's Spring Street Cafe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princetonsrestaurants.com/restaurant/Princeton-NJ/Chuck%27s-Spring-Street-Cafe |title=Chuck's Spring Street Cafe in Princeton, NJ  |publisher=Princetonsrestaurants.com |date= |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref> a [[Buffalo wing]] restaurant in [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]], [[New Jersey]] while Erik hired a full-time tennis coach and competed in a series of tournaments in [[Israel]]. They eventually left the family mansion unoccupied, as they decided to live in adjoining condos in nearby [[Marina del Rey, California|Marina del Rey]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.refinery29.com/2017/09/174002/menendez-brothers-money-spent-shopping-law-and-order|title=Here's How Much The Menendez Brothers Spent On Their Spree|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref> They also drove around [[Los Angeles]] in their deceased mother's [[Mercedes-Benz SL-Class|Mercedes-Benz SL]] convertible, dined expensively, and went on overseas trips to the [[Caribbean]] and [[London]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/883055/lost-in-l-a-this-menendez-brothers-murder-map-will-help-you-put-the-crazy-sprawling-story-into-perspective|title=This Menendez Brothers Murder Map Puts the Crazy Story in Perspective|work=E! Online|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> It is believed that they spent somewhere around $700,000 during the time period between the murders and their arrests.<ref name=\"vf\"/>\n\nDuring the early stages of the investigation, the police tried to narrow their search down to people who would have had motives to kill Jos\u00e9 and Kitty. One of these people included a pornography distributor named Noel C. Bloom,<ref name=johnson/> but he was found to have had no involvement and was quickly cleared. They also investigated potential mob leads, but nothing came out of those leads. As the investigation continued, the police believed that the brothers were most likely the culprits since they had obvious financial motives and were spending lots of money just after the murders. In an attempt to get a confession from Erik, the police got Craig Cignarelli, one of Erik's close friends from high school and tennis buddy, to wear a wire while having lunch with him at a local beachfront restaurant.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/1993/10/dunne199310|title=The Menendez Murder Trial|last=Dunne|first=Dominick|authorlink=Dominick Dunne|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|language=en|date=September 15, 2008|access-date=May 10, 2019}}</ref> When Craig asked Erik if he killed his parents, Erik initially said no, but eventually confessed to doing so to his [[psychologist]] Jerome Oziel. After Lyle threatened him, Oziel told his mistress Judalon Smyth about the murders, and she told the police about the brothers' involvement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-11-16/local/me-57401_1_stormy-affair|title=Menendez Therapist's Ex-Lover Testifies : Trial: She says Oziel wanted the brothers to confess on tape so he could 'control' them. Calls that the woman secretly recorded of the stormy affair are also played in court.|last=Abrahamson|first=Alan|date=November 16, 1993|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> Lyle was arrested on March 8, 1990, and Erik turned himself in three days later after returning to Los Angeles from Israel. Both were held without bail and separated from each other.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/crime-files/menendez-brothers/arrest|title=The Arrest|date=June 29, 2017|work=Crime + Investigation|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref> In August 1990, Judge James Albrecht stated that tapes of the conversations between Erik and Oziel were admissible since Lyle violated [[physician\u2013patient privilege|doctor\u2013patient privilege]] by threatening Oziel. However, since that ruling was appealed, the proceedings were delayed for two years. The Supreme Court of California then stated in August 1992 that most of these tapes were admissible except the one of Erik discussing the murders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/california/supreme-court/4th/3/435.html|title=Menendez v. Superior Court (People) (1992)|work=Justia Law|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref> After that decision, a Los Angeles County grand jury issued indictments in December 1992, charging the brothers with the murders of their parents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-12-30/local/me-2458_1_grand-jury|title=Menendez Brothers Plead Innocent in Killings : Court: Grand jury indictment means trial in the deaths of their parents could begin in March.|last=McMilla|first=Penelope|date=December 30, 1992|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\n==Trials==\nThe case became a national sensation when [[Court TV]] broadcast the trial in 1993.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/article/1993/11/12/confessions-court-tv-addict/|title=Confessions of a Court TV Addict|last=Cagle|first=Jess|date=November 12, 1993|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=June 9, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> Their defense lawyer [[Leslie Abramson]] became known for her theory that the brothers were driven to murder by a lifetime of [[child abuse|abuse]] at the hands of their parents, especially [[abuse defense|sexual abuse]] at the hands of their father, who was described as a cruel [[perfectionism (psychology)|perfectionist]] and [[pedophilia|pedophile]]. Meanwhile, their mother was described as a selfish, mentally unstable [[alcoholism|alcoholic]] and [[drug addict]] who encouraged her husband's abuses and was also sometimes violent towards them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/notorious_murders/famous/menendez/trial_16.html | title=The Men\u00e9ndez Brothers |accessdate=December 3, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012213355/http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/notorious_murders/famous/menendez/trial_16.html |archivedate=October 12, 2012}}</ref> The trial ended with two deadlocked juries as a result, and Los Angeles County District Attorney Gil Garcetti announced immediately that the brothers would be retried. The second trial was somewhat less publicized, partly because Judge Stanley Weisberg did not allow cameras in the courtroom.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chiasson|first1=Lloyd|title=The Press on Trial: Crimes and Trials as Media Events|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|location=Westport, Connecticut|date=1997|page=200|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qdGpzU_qWA0C&pg=PA200&lpg=PA200&dq=stanley+weisberg+refuse+cameras+menendez#v=onepage&q=stanley%20weisberg%20refuse%20cameras%20menendez&f=false|accessdate=June 3, 2015|isbn=9780313300226}}</ref> Also during the second trial, Weisberg did not allow much defense testimony about the sexual abuse claims<ref>{{cite web|title=Legal Loophole Could Give Murderous Brothers Erik And Lyle Menendez Chance For New Trial|url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/11/17/legal-loophole-could-give-murderous-brothers-erik-lyle-menendez-chance-for-new-trial|website=[[CBS Los Angeles]]|date=November 17, 2016}}</ref> and did not allow the jury to vote on manslaughter charges instead of murder charges.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tammi Menendez on Loving Erik|url=http://abcnews.go.com/2020/story?id=123804&page=1|website=[[ABC News]]|date=September 27, 2002}}</ref>\n\nBoth brothers were eventually convicted of two counts of first-degree murder and conspiracy to commit murder, and in the penalty phase of the trial, they were sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole. The jury said that the abuse defense was not a factor in its deliberations, but chose not to impose the death penalty because both brothers had no criminal record or history of violence prior to the murders of their parents. However, unlike the juries in the previous trials, the jury in the penalty phase rejected the defense's theory that the brothers had killed their parents out of fear, as it is believed that they committed the murders in order to inherit their father's wealth.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Abrahamson|first1=Alan|title=Little Remains of Men\u00e9ndez Estate, Records Show : Courts: Inheritance of $14.5&nbsp;million was lost to taxes, lawyers' fees and inflated real estate appraisals, probate files reveal|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-04-03/local/me-41704_1_real-estate-appraisals|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 3, 1994}}</ref> During the penalty phase of the trial, Abramson apparently told a defense witness named William Vicary to edit his notes, but the district attorney's office decided not to conduct a criminal investigation.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/12/us/menendez-lawyer-won-t-face-investigation.html |title = Menendez Lawyer Won't Face Investigation | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = October 12, 1997 | accessdate = May 26, 2014 }}</ref> Both brothers also filed motions for a mistrial, claiming that they had suffered irreversible damage in the penalty phase as a result of possible misconduct and ineffective representation by Abramson. On July 2, 1996, Weisberg sentenced the brothers to life in prison without the possibility of parole, and also sentenced them to consecutive sentences for the murders and the charges of conspiracy to commit murder.\n\n==Incarceration==\nJust like their pretrial detention, the California Department of Corrections separated the brothers and sent them to different prisons. Since they were considered to be maximum-security inmates, they were segregated from other prisoners. They remained in separate prisons until February 2018 when Lyle was moved from [[Mule Creek State Prison]] in Northern California to the [[Richard J. Donovan Correctional Facility]]<ref>[https://inmatelocator.cdcr.ca.gov/Details.aspx?ID=K14101 State of California Inmate Locator] \u2013 CDCR</ref> in San Diego County, but were housed in separate units until April 4, 2018 when Lyle was moved to the same housing unit as Erik, reuniting them for the first time since they began serving their sentences nearly 22 years earlier. Both brothers burst into tears and hugged each other at their first meeting in the housing unit. The unit where the brothers are housed is reserved for inmates who agree to participate in educational and other rehabilitation programs without creating disruptions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Menendez brothers who killed parents reunited in California prison|url=http://freep.mi.newsmemory.com/?token=62b248b84fa909472d7737ac1bb2b800&cnum=7361672&fod=1111111STD&selDate=20180407&licenseType=paid_subscriber&|accessdate=April 7, 2018|issue=|publisher=Detroit Free Press|date=April 7, 2018|page=3C|language=English|format=newspaper}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/parent-killing-menendez-brothers-burst-tears-reuniting-article-1.3918859|title=Parent-killing Menendez brothers 'burst into tears' upon reuniting for first time since sentencing|author=Sommerfeldt, Chris|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=2018-04-06|accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Menendez brothers convicted of killing parents reunite in jail|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-43663451|website=bbc.com|date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Appeals==\nOn February 27, 1998, the California Court of Appeal upheld their murder convictions, and on May 28, 1998, the Supreme Court of California upheld their murder convictions and sentences without any Supreme Court judges reviewing the case.<ref name=\"Crime Library\"/> Both brothers filed ''[[habeas corpus]]'' petitions with the Supreme Court of California, which were denied in 1999. Having exhausted their appeal remedies in state court, they filed separate habeas corpus petitions in the United States District Court. On March 4, 2003, a magistrate judge recommended the denial of the petitions,{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} and the district court adopted the recommendation. They then decided to appeal to the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit. On September 7, 2005, a three-judge panel denied both their habeas corpus petitions,<ref>{{cite web|title=United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit |url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2005/09/07/0355863.pdf|website=uscourts.gov|accessdate=June 8, 2017}}</ref> although Judge Alex Kozinski stated that the trial judge changed many of his rulings during the two trials.<ref>{{cite web|title=Law Offices of Cliff Gardner|url=http://www.cliffgardner.com/resources/menendez.mp3|website=cliffgardner.com/index.php|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Marriages and interviews in prison==\nOn July 2, 1996, Lyle married Anna Eriksson at a ceremony attended by Abramson and his aunt Marta Men\u00e9ndez, which was presided over by Judge Nancy Brown, but they divorced on April 1, 2001<ref name=\"Crime Library\" /> after Eriksson discovered that Lyle was allegedly cheating on her with another woman. In November 2003, Lyle married Rebecca Sneed at a ceremony in a supermax prison visiting area of [[Mule Creek State Prison]], and they knew each other for around ten years before their engagement.<ref>{{cite web|first=Dan|last=Abrams|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/12134256|title=Should single guys trade their pinstripes for prison stripes?|website=NBC News|date=January 18, 2006|accessdate=September 2, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/3540836|title=Parent killer Men\u00e9ndez marries in Calif. prison|website=NBC News|date=November 23, 2003|accessdate=September 2, 2008}}</ref> On June 12, 1999, Erik married Tammi Ruth Saccoman at [[Folsom State Prison]] in a prison waiting room. Tammi later stated: \"Our wedding cake was a Twinkie. We improvised. It was a wonderful ceremony until I had to leave. That was a very lonely night.\"<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine|first=Bill|last=Hewitt|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20144791,00.html|title=Life & Love Behind Bars|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=November 7, 2005|volume=64|number=19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://edition.cnn.com/US/9906/16/menendez/| title=Convicted murderer Erik Men\u00e9ndez marries in prison | website=[[CNN]]|date= June 16, 1999 | accessdate =July 19, 2008}}</ref> In an October 2005 interview with [[ABC News]], she described her relationship with Erik as \"something that I've dreamed about for a long time. And it's just something very special that I never thought that I would ever have.\"<ref name=ABC1>{{cite news | url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=1255023| title=Erik Men\u00e9ndez's Life Behind Bars| website= [[ABC News]] |date= October 25, 2005 | accessdate =July 19, 2008}}</ref> In 2005, Tammi self-published a book titled ''They Said We'd Never Make It \u2013 My Life With Erik Men\u00e9ndez'', but she said on ''[[Larry King Live]]'' that Erik also \"did a lot of editing on the book.\"<ref name=\"cnn_tammy\">{{cite news | accessdate=2015-06-13 | date= December 20, 2005 | publisher=CNN | title=Interview With Tammi Men\u00e9ndez | url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0512/20/lkl.01.html}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2005 interview with ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine, she stated: \"Not having sex in my life is difficult, but it's not a problem for me. I have to be emotionally attached, and I'm emotionally attached to Erik.... My family does not understand. When it started to get serious, some of them just threw up their hands.\" Tammi also stated that she and her daughter drive the {{convert|150|mi}} every weekend to visit Erik, and that her daughter refers to him as her \"Earth Dad.\"<ref name=\"people\" /> Despite his life sentence, Erik stated: \"Tammi is what gets me through. I can't think about the sentence. When I do, I do it with a great sadness and a primal fear. I break into a cold sweat. It's so frightening I just haven't come to terms with it.\"<ref name=\"people\" /> In 2010, [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] released a documentary about Tammi titled ''Mrs. Men\u00e9ndez''.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|title=Men\u00e9ndez brothers convicted in parents' murder 16 years ago|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/03/menendez-brothers.html|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 20, 2012}}</ref> In late 2017, A&E aired a five-part documentary titled ''The Menendez Murders: Erik Tells All'' in which Erik, via telephone, recalls the murders and the aftermath. The series also shows never-before-seen photos and new interviews with prosecutors, law enforcement, close family and friends, and medical experts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/menendez-murders-erik-tells-all/listings/|title=The Menendez Murders: Erik Tells All|website=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=November 30, 2017|accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe ''[[Law & Order]]'' Season 1 episode \"[[Law & Order (season_1)#ep19|The Serpent's Tooth]]\" is loosley based on the The Menendez Brothers case. The Menendez brothers were also featured in a 2017 documentary titled ''Truth and Lies: The Men\u00e9ndez Brothers \u2013 American Sons, American Murderers'' on ABC, as well as on an episode of ''[[Snapped]]'' in 2016. The murders are the subjects of multiple docu-dramas, including the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] movie ''[[Menendez: Blood Brothers]]'' (2017), and the television films ''[[Menendez: A Killing in Beverly Hills]]'' on CBS and ''Honor Thy Father and Mother: The True Story of the Menendez Murders'' on Fox, both in 1994. The media hype surrounding the first trial was parodied in the 1996 dark comedy film ''[[The Cable Guy]]''. The Men\u00e9ndez brothers were subjects of the weekly satire podcast ''[[The Last Podcast on the Left]]'' in 2016 and were depicted in the film ''[[Natural Born Killers]]''. Their story was also featured in an episode of ''Barbara Walters Presents: American Scandals'' titled \"Menendez Brothers: The Bad Sons\" and in a documentary series from Court TV, now TruTV, in an episode titled ''Mugshots: Menendez Brothers \u2013 Blood Brothers'' in 2000 at ''[[FilmRise]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mugshots: Menendez Brothers|url=http://filmrise.com/mugshots-menendez-brothers/|website=FilmRise|accessdate=November 8, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mugshots (TV Series 2000)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0320080/episodes?ref_=tt_ov_epl|website=imdb.com|accessdate=October 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Menendez Brothers \u2013 Blood Brothers: Ellen Goosenberg Kent|url=https://www.amazon.com/Mugshots-Menendez-Brothers-Blood/dp/B00D0XOBSQ|website=www.amazon.com|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Law & Order True Crime|Law & Order True Crime: The Men\u00e9ndez Murders]]'' premiered on NBC in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/09/26/entertainment/law-and-order-true-crime-menendez-murders-review/index.html|title='Law & Order True Crime: The Menendez Murders' review|last=Lowry|first=Brian|date=September 26, 2017|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> In addition, Season 4, Episode One of ''[[Jake and the Fatman]]'', entitled '''God Bless the Child''' appears to be based upon these killings, with the son and daughter of a shipping magnate kill him and their stepmother, so as not to lose their inheritance.\n\n[[HLN (TV network)|HLN]] launched the new series [[HLN (TV network)#Programming|''How it Really Happened with Hill Harper'']], with an episode featuring the Men\u00e9ndez brothers story. The episode is titled \"The Men\u00e9ndez Brothers: Murder in Beverly Hills\",  and it ends with a telephone interview of Lyle from jail with [[Chris Cuomo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=How It Really Happened with Hill Harper {{!}} The Menendez Brothers: Murder in Beverly Hills|url=http://www.cnn.com/interactive/2017/hln/how-it-really-happened/the-menendez-brothers/|accessdate=October 14, 2017|work=HLN|publisher=Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.|date=January 27, 2017}}</ref> The Menendez brothers are believed to be in the background of the [[1990\u201391 NBA season|1990\u201391]] NBA Hoops [[Mark Jackson (basketball)|Mark Jackson]] basketball card in which the [[New York Knicks]] point guard is seen making a bounce pass and they appear to be sitting courtside behind Jackson.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Skiver |first1=Kevin |title=Menendez brothers appear in background of Mark Jackson basketball card |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/menendez-brothers-appear-in-background-of-mark-jackson-basketball-card/ |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |publisher=CBS Sports |date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, [[eBay]] began pulling auctions in which they are mentioned in the listing. The New York Knicks had played 28 games during the period when the Menendez brothers went on a spending spree after the murders of their parents. Some eBay sellers have continued to sell the card and have also altered the images accompanying the listing so that the men purported to be the Menendez brothers are neither mentioned in the listing nor seen in photos of the card accompanying the listing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=D'Angelo |first1=Bob |title=Double Take: Infamous Menendez Brothers and the 1990\u201391 Hoops Mark Jackson |url=https://www.sportscollectorsdaily.com/double-take-infamous-menendez-brothers-and-the-1990-91-hoops-mark-jackson/ |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |publisher=Sports Collectors Daily |date=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Parricide]]\n* [[Stacey Lannert]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n===Books===\n* Davis, Don (1994) ''Bad Blood: The Shocking True Story Behind the Men\u00e9ndez Killings'' St. Martin, New York, {{ISBN|0-312-95334-8}}\n* Men\u00e9ndez, Lyle; Novelli, Norma; Walker, Mike; and Spreckels, Judith (1995) ''The Private Diary of Lyle Men\u00e9ndez: In His Own Words!'' Dove Books, Beverly Hills, California, {{ISBN|0-7871-0474-4}}\n* Men\u00e9ndez, Tammi (2005) ''They Said We'd Never Make It: My Life With Erik Men\u00e9ndez'' NewGalen Publishing, Santa Clarita, California, {{ISBN|0-9768744-0-7}}\n* Soble, Ronald L. and Johnson, John (1994) ''Blood Brothers: The Inside Story of the Men\u00e9ndez Murders'' Onyx, New York, {{ISBN|0-451-40547-1}}\n* Thornton, Hazel; Wrightsman, Lawrence S.; Posey, Amy J. and Scheflin, Alan W. (1995) ''Hung Jury: The Diary of a Men\u00e9ndez Juror'' Temple University Press, Philadelphia; new \"20 Years Later\" edition updated with new material, Graymalkin Media (2017) {{ISBN|978-1631681622}}\n* Rand, Robert (2018) ''The Menendez Murders: The Shocking Untold Story of the Menendez Family and the Killings that Stunned the Nation'' BenBella Books {{ISBN|978-1946885265}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/archive/1990/10/dunne199010 Nightmare on Elm Drive] by [[Dominick Dunne]]. ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', October 1990\n* [http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/archive/1996/06/dunne199606 Three Faces of Evil] by [[Dominick Dunne]]. ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', June 1996\n* [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/10573267 Wife of Erik Men\u00e9ndez talks about relationship] at MSNBC TV, December 22, 2005\n* [http://abcnews.go.com/2020/Story?id=123804&page=1 Tammi Men\u00e9ndez on Loving Erik] at [[ABC News]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061006112240/http://www.courttv.com/trials/menendez/ Men\u00e9ndez Brothers] at Court TV (now [[TruTV]])\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061107093811/http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/famous/menendez/index_1.html Men\u00e9ndez Brothers] at [[Crime Library]]\n* [http://www.thesmokinggun.com/mugshots/menendezmug1.html Mug shots of the brothers] on [[The Smoking Gun]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20000818085030/http://www.courttv.com/casefiles/menendez/transcripts/ archived trial transcripts] from Court TV\n* {{LCAuth|n94062388|Lyle Men\u00e9ndez|1|}}\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-n94-062388|Lyle Men\u00e9ndez}}\n* [http://lccn.loc.gov/n94062384 Erik Men\u00e9ndez] at LC Authorities, with no records<!-- 2015-04-28 -->\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-n94-062384|Erik Men\u00e9ndez}}\n\n<!-- some categories individual to one person, e.g., birth and death year or living person are under the redirect for that person -->\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Men\u00e9ndez, Lyle and Erik}}\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:1989 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:People from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Criminal duos]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Parricides]]\n[[Category:American prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:People from Hopewell Township, Mercer County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Princeton, New Jersey]