{"title_page": "Tamara Adri\u00e1n", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Tamara Adri\u00e1n\n|image              = Tamara Adri\u00e1n.jpg\n|imagesize          = 200px\n|caption            = Adri\u00e1n in 2008\n|office             = Alternate Deputy of the<br />[[National Assembly of Venezuela]]\n|term_start         = 5 January 2016\n|term_end           = \n|predecessor        = \n|constituency       = [[Capital District (Venezuela)|Capital District]]\n|majority           = \n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1954|2|20|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]\n|citizenship        = \n|nationality        = \n|party              = [[Popular Will]]\n|otherparty         = \n|spouse             = \n|partner            = \n|relations          = \n|children           = \n|alma_mater         = [[Andr\u00e9s Bello Catholic University]]\n|occupation         = \n|profession         = [[Lawyer]]\n|religion           = \n|signature          = \n|signature_alt      = \n|website            = \n}}\n'''Tamara Adri\u00e1n''' (born 20 February 1954, in [[Caracas]]) is a [[Venezuela]]n politician, who was elected to the [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly of Venezuela]] in the [[2015 Venezuelan parliamentary election]].<ref name=aldia>[http://noticiaaldia.com/2015/12/tamara-adrian-se-convierte-en-la-primera-diputada-transgenero-en-la-historia-de-venezuela/ \"Tamara Adri\u00e1n se convierte en la primera diputada transg\u00e9nero en la historia de Venezuela\"]. ''Noticia Al D\u00eda'', December 7, 2015.</ref> She is noted as the first [[transgender]] person elected to office in Venezuela, and only the second transgender sgmember of a national legislature in the Western Hemisphere.<ref name=out>[http://www.out.com/news-opinion/2015/12/07/venezuela-elects-first-transgender-congresswoman-continent \"Venezuela Elects First Transgender Congresswoman in the Americas\"]. ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'', December 7, 2015.</ref> Some early media coverage credited her as the first transgender member of a legislature in the Americas, but this was later corrected due to the election of [[Michelle Su\u00e1rez B\u00e9rtora]] to the [[Senate of Uruguay]] in 2014.<ref name=out/>\n\nShe is a member of the [[Popular Will]] party, one of the forces in opposition to the [[United Socialist Party of Venezuela|PSUV]]-led government of [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]].<ref name=out/> She took her [[oath of office]] at the [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly of Venezuela]] on January 14, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.voluntadpopular.com/index.php/ver-noticia/component/content/article/8-noticias/4079-asamblea-nacional-juramento-a-tamara-adrian-primera-diputada-transgenero-en-venezuela|title=Asamblea Nacional jurament\u00f3 a Tamara Adri\u00e1n, primera diputada transg\u00e9nero en Venezuela|website=www.voluntadpopular.com|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> During her term in office, Adri\u00e1n intends to promote proper access to [[public records]] on identity, [[same-sex marriage]] and [[human rights]].\n\nPrior to her election to the Venezuelan legislature, Adri\u00e1n worked as a lawyer and [[LGBT]] activist,<ref name=smh>[http://www.smh.com.au/world/venezuelas-first-transgender-candidate-tamara-adrian-to-run-for-congress-20150808-giuj5i.html \"Venezuela's first transgender candidate Tamara Adri\u00e1n to run for Congress\"]. ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'', August 8, 2015.</ref> including serving on the board of the [[International Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Intersex Association]]<ref name=aldia/> and the organizing committee of the [[International Day Against Homophobia, Transphobia and Biphobia]].<ref>[http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2015/05/17/meet-women-fighting-transphobia-across-americas \"Meet the Women Fighting Transphobia Across the Americas\"]. ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', May 17, 2015.</ref> She was forced to register her candidacy under her male birth name, as Venezuelan law does not currently permit a person that was [[assigned male at birth]] to legally change their name to a female name.<ref name=smh/> In 2014, she submitted an appeal to the [[Supreme Court of Justice of Venezuela|Supreme Court of Justice]] to have her identity legally recognized but it still has not granted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://glxy.eu/news/1026-tamara-adrian-the-first-transgender-deputy-from-latin-america-elected-in-venezuela|title=Tamara Adri\u00e1n, the first transgender deputy from Latin America, elected in Venezuela.|last=Tovar|first=Eugenia|website=glxy.eu|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> \n\nTamara Adri\u00e1n believes that the [[Social stigma|stigma]] and discrimination surrounding the transgendered community stimulates poverty, [[marginalization]], and violence against them. To her, these problems are unacceptable under international laws of human rights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2015/05/17/meet-women-fighting-transphobia-across-americas|title=Meet the Women Fighting Transphobia Across the Americas|date=2015-05-17|website=www.advocate.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> She was motivated to take a role in her government in response to political activists being arrested in Venezuela<ref>{{Citation|title=Tamara Adrian {{!}} Moving from Activism to Governance|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dm1TkJRHZqc|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>. In 2014, there were [[2014 Venezuelan protests|many protests]] regarding the democratic and economic conditions of the time. In response to these protests, President [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] ordered for the arrest of political protestors. According to [[Foro Penal]], over 13,000 people have been arrested since 2014 because of protests relating to the Venezuelan government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/01/25/venezuela-arrests-killings-anti-government-protests|title=Venezuela: Arrests, Killings in Anti-Government Protests|last=Avenue|first=Human Rights Watch {{!}} 350 Fifth|last2=York|first2=34th Floor {{!}} New|date=2019-01-25|website=Human Rights Watch|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05|last3=t 1.212.290.4700|first3=NY 10118-3299 USA {{!}}}}</ref>\n\nTamara graduated from [[Andr\u00e9s Bello Catholic University]] in 1976. She then went on to obtain her doctorate in law with high honors from University of Paris II Panth\u00e9on-Assasin in 1982. She also earned a diploma in comparative law from the [[Paris Institute of Comparative Law]] in 1982.\n\n==See also ==\n\n*[[LGBT rights in Venezuela]]\n*[[List of the first LGBT holders of political offices]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adrian, Tamara}}\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Venezuela)]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan women in politics]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual politicians]]\n[[Category:Popular Will politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from Venezuela]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual women]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Caracas]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Andr\u00e9s Bello Catholic University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan women activists]]\n[[Category:LGBT legislators]]\n\n\n{{Venezuela-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Tamara Adri\u00e1n\n|image              = Tamara Adri\u00e1n.jpg\n|imagesize          = 200px\n|caption            = Adri\u00e1n in 2008\n|office             = Alternate Deputy of the<br />[[National Assembly of Venezuela]]\n|term_start         = 5 January 2016\n|term_end           = \n|predecessor        = \n|constituency       = [[Capital District (Venezuela)|Capital District]]\n|majority           = \n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1954|2|20|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]\n|citizenship        = \n|nationality        = \n|party              = [[Popular Will]]\n|otherparty         = \n|spouse             = \n|partner            = \n|relations          = \n|children           = \n|alma_mater         = [[Andr\u00e9s Bello Catholic University]]\n|occupation         = \n|profession         = [[Lawyer]]\n|religion           = \n|signature          = \n|signature_alt      = \n|website            = \n}}\n'''Tamara Adri\u00e1n''' (born 20 February 1954, in [[Caracas]]) is a [[Venezuela]]n politician, who was elected to the [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly of Venezuela]] in the [[2015 Venezuelan parliamentary election]].<ref name=aldia>[http://noticiaaldia.com/2015/12/tamara-adrian-se-convierte-en-la-primera-diputada-transgenero-en-la-historia-de-venezuela/ \"Tamara Adri\u00e1n se convierte en la primera diputada transg\u00e9nero en la historia de Venezuela\"]. ''Noticia Al D\u00eda'', December 7, 2015.</ref> She is noted as the first [[transgender]] person elected to office in Venezuela, and only the second transgender sgmember of a national legislature in the Western Hemisphere.<ref name=out>[http://www.out.com/news-opinion/2015/12/07/venezuela-elects-first-transgender-congresswoman-continent \"Venezuela Elects First Transgender Congresswoman in the Americas\"]. ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'', December 7, 2015.</ref> Some early media coverage credited her as the first transgender member of a legislature in the Americas, but this was later corrected due to the election of [[Michelle Su\u00e1rez B\u00e9rtora]] to the [[Senate of Uruguay]] in 2014.<ref name=out/>\n\nShe is a member of the [[Popular Will]] party, one of the forces in opposition to the [[United Socialist Party of Venezuela|PSUV]]-led government of [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]].<ref name=out/> She took her [[oath of office]] at the [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly of Venezuela]] on January 14, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.voluntadpopular.com/index.php/ver-noticia/component/content/article/8-noticias/4079-asamblea-nacional-juramento-a-tamara-adrian-primera-diputada-transgenero-en-venezuela|title=Asamblea Nacional jurament\u00f3 a Tamara Adri\u00e1n, primera diputada transg\u00e9nero en Venezuela|website=www.voluntadpopular.com|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> During her term in office, Adri\u00e1n intends to promote proper access to [[public records]] on identity, [[same-sex marriage]] and [[human rights]].\n\nPrior to her election to the Venezuelan legislature, Adri\u00e1n worked as a lawyer and [[LGBT]] activist,<ref name=smh>[http://www.smh.com.au/world/venezuelas-first-transgender-candidate-tamara-adrian-to-run-for-congress-20150808-giuj5i.html \"Venezuela's first transgender candidate Tamara Adri\u00e1n to run for Congress\"]. ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'', August 8, 2015.</ref> including serving on the board of the [[International Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Intersex Association]]<ref name=aldia/> and the organizing committee of the [[International Day Against Homophobia, Transphobia and Biphobia]].<ref>[http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2015/05/17/meet-women-fighting-transphobia-across-americas \"Meet the Women Fighting Transphobia Across the Americas\"]. ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', May 17, 2015.</ref> She was forced to register her candidacy under her male birth name, as Venezuelan law does not currently permit a person that was [[assigned male at birth]] to legally change their name to a female name.<ref name=smh/> In 2014, she submitted an appeal to the [[Supreme Court of Justice of Venezuela|Supreme Court of Justice]] to have her identity legally recognized but it still has not granted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://glxy.eu/news/1026-tamara-adrian-the-first-transgender-deputy-from-latin-america-elected-in-venezuela|title=Tamara Adri\u00e1n, the first transgender deputy from Latin America, elected in Venezuela.|last=Tovar|first=Eugenia|website=glxy.eu|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> \n\nTamara Adri\u00e1n believes that the [[Social stigma|stigma]] and discrimination surrounding the transgendered community stimulates poverty, [[marginalization]], and violence against them. To her, these problems are unnacceptable under international laws of human rights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2015/05/17/meet-women-fighting-transphobia-across-americas|title=Meet the Women Fighting Transphobia Across the Americas|date=2015-05-17|website=www.advocate.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> She was motivated to take a role in her government in response to political activists being arrested in Venezuela<ref>{{Citation|title=Tamara Adrian {{!}} Moving from Activism to Governance|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dm1TkJRHZqc|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>. In 2014, there were [[2014 Venezuelan protests|many protests]] regarding the democratic and economic conditions of the time. In response to these protests, President [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] ordered for the arrest of political protestors. According to [[Foro Penal]], over 13,000 people have been arrested since 2014 because of protests relating to the Venezuelan government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/01/25/venezuela-arrests-killings-anti-government-protests|title=Venezuela: Arrests, Killings in Anti-Government Protests|last=Avenue|first=Human Rights Watch {{!}} 350 Fifth|last2=York|first2=34th Floor {{!}} New|date=2019-01-25|website=Human Rights Watch|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05|last3=t 1.212.290.4700|first3=NY 10118-3299 USA {{!}}}}</ref>\n\nTamara graduated from [[Andr\u00e9s Bello Catholic University]] in 1976. She then went on to obtain her doctorate in law with high honors from University of Paris II Panth\u00e9on-Assasin in 1982. She also earned a diploma in comparative law from the [[Paris Institute of Comparative Law]] in 1982.\n\n==See also ==\n\n*[[LGBT rights in Venezuela]]\n*[[List of the first LGBT holders of political offices]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adrian, Tamara}}\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Venezuela)]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan women in politics]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual politicians]]\n[[Category:Popular Will politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from Venezuela]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual women]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Caracas]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Andr\u00e9s Bello Catholic University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan women activists]]\n[[Category:LGBT legislators]]\n\n\n{{Venezuela-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "unnacceptable->unacceptable -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tamara_Adri%C3%A1n"}
{"title_page": "Zhou Meisen", "text_new": "{{Chinese name|[[Zhou (surname)|Zhou]]}}\n'''Zhou Meisen''' ({{zh|c=|s=\u5468\u6885\u68ee|t=|p=Zh\u014du M\u00e9is\u0113n}}; born 9 March 1956) is a contemporary Chinese novelist and scriptwriter. He is active in literary mainland China since the 1980s. He is well known for some of his works which have been adapted for screen, especially ''[[In the Name of People|In the Name of the People]]''.\n\nZhou was born on 9 March 1956, in [[Jiangsu]].<!-- Zhou was born in Xuzhou or Yangzhou is not clear according the articles. So perhaps it is not necessary to mention the specificity.~Med Nyin, May 2017. --> He grew&nbsp;up&nbsp;in [[Jiawang District|Jiawang]], &nbsp;a&nbsp;suburb of [[Xuzhou]] with plentiful coal&nbsp;capacity. Later, he went to a high school, as a part-time student, working for a local pit. He became a miner after he&nbsp;left&nbsp;school. Thus, Zhou's earlier writings focus on coal industry and miners.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=\u5468\u6885\u68ee\u4f5c\u8005\u7b80\u4ecb|url=|journal=\u626c\u5b50\u6c5f\u8bc4\u8bba|volume=2012|issue=2|pages=2}}</ref>&nbsp; When he was 14 years old, he knew [[Honor\u00e9 de Balzac|Balzac]] by chance. From then on, Zhou adores him and professes [[Realism (arts)|realism]] should be the guideline of own writing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinawriter.com.cn/n1/2017/0421/c405057-29225716.html|title=\u5468\u6885\u68ee\uff1a\u575a\u6301\u73b0\u5b9e\u4e3b\u4e49\u521b\u4f5c\u662f\u6211\u4e0d\u53d8\u7684\u6587\u5b66\u4fe1\u4ef0|date=21 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1970s, Zhou published his first work in ''[[Xinhua Daily]]''. A year later, he was transferred to Nanjing, working as an editor for ''Youth'', a recently-started magazine. He gained initial fame with his 1983 novella ''The Sinking Land'' ({{lang-zh|\u6c89\u6ca6\u7684\u571f\u5730}}),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2017-03/30/content_28731717.htm|title=Writer praised for anti-graft drama|website=China Daily}}{{dead link|date=January 2019}}</ref> then he became a professional writer since 1984. In the mid 1990s, he spent one year on secondment to a municipal government as deputy secretary general&nbsp;.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.infzm.com/content/122954|title=\"\u6211\u8ba4\u8bc6\u7684\u5f88\u591a\u5b98\u5458\u90fd'\u8fdb\u53bb'\u4e86\"  \u5468\u6885\u68ee\u7684\u653f\u6cbb\u5c0f\u8bf4\u65b0\u4f5c\u300a\u4eba\u6c11\u7684\u540d\u4e49\u300b|work=Southern Weekly}}</ref> In the meantime, he attempted to make a decent living by investing in business, stock and real estate.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=\u6211\u8981\u6811\u7acb\u81ea\u5df1\u7684\u54c1\u724c\u2014\u2014\u5468\u6885\u68ee\u8bbf\u8c08|url=|journal=\u5927\u4f17\u7535\u5f71|volume=2004|issue=4|pages=28\u201330}}</ref> The&nbsp;broad experience inspired him, and suffuses in his works.\n\nZhou's novels and scripts of the anti-graft dramas are in the public gaze. To make the plot vivid, he even visited a jail and interviewed the detained officials for corruption.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.cjn.cn/sywh/201704/t2994373.htm|title=\u5468\u6885\u68ee\uff1a\u300a\u4eba\u6c11\u7684\u540d\u4e49\u300b\u8fd9\u6761\u8239\u4e0a\u642d\u8f7d\u7684\u4e1c\u897f\u5f88\u591a|work=\u957f\u6c5f\u65e5\u62a5}}</ref>\n\nAs a major individual shareholder of some a listed&nbsp;company, Zhou published his open letters and called on individual investors against its reform of non-tradable shares to unite in 2005, since he claimed such a reform damages&nbsp;the&nbsp;interests&nbsp;of them. Eventually, the shareholders' meeting voted that down. The news caused a strong reaction among the individual investors, so he became the candidate for [[CCTV-2|CCTV]] Person of the Year for Social Common&nbsp;Good ({{lang-zh|\u793e\u4f1a\u516c\u76ca\u4eba\u7269}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/fortune/2005-12/06/content_3884017_22.htm|title=2005CCTV\u4e2d\u56fd\u7ecf\u6d4e\u5e74\u5ea6\u4eba\u726925\u4f4d\u5019\u9009\u4eba|website=Xinhua News}}{{dead link|date=January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''The Sinking Land''\n* ''Supreme Interest'' ({{lang-zh|\u81f3\u9ad8\u5229\u76ca}})\n* ''State Prosecution'' ({{lang-zh|\u56fd\u5bb6\u516c\u8bc9}})\n* ''[[In the Name of People|In the Name of the People]]''\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chinese novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Chinese novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Xuzhou]]\n[[Category:Chinese male novelists]]\n[[Category:Chinese television writers]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chinese male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Jiangsu]]\n", "text_old": "{{Chinese name|[[Zhou (surname)|Zhou]]}}\n'''Zhou Meisen''' ({{zh|c=|s=\u5468\u6885\u68ee|t=|p=Zh\u014du M\u00e9is\u0113n}}; born 9 March 1956) is a contemporary Chinese novelist and scriptwriter. He is active in literary mainland China since the 1980s. He is well known for some of his works which have been adapted for screen, especially ''[[In the Name of People|In the Name of the People]]''.\n\nZhou was born on 9 March 1956, in [[Jiangsu]].<!-- Zhou was born in Xuzhou or Yangzhou is not clear according the articles. So perhaps it is not necessary to mention the specificity.~Med Nyin, May 2017. --> He grew&nbsp;up&nbsp;in [[Jiawang District|Jiawang]], &nbsp;a&nbsp;suburb of [[Xuzhou]] with plentiful coal&nbsp;capacity. Later, he went to a high school, as a part-time student, working for a local pit. He became a miner after he&nbsp;left&nbsp;school. Thus, Zhou's earlier writings focus on coal industry and miners.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=\u5468\u6885\u68ee\u4f5c\u8005\u7b80\u4ecb|url=|journal=\u626c\u5b50\u6c5f\u8bc4\u8bba|volume=2012|issue=2|pages=2}}</ref>&nbsp; When he was 14 years old, he knew [[Honor\u00e9 de Balzac|Balzac]] by chance. From then on, Zhou adores him and professes [[Realism (arts)|realism]] should be the guideline of own writing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinawriter.com.cn/n1/2017/0421/c405057-29225716.html|title=\u5468\u6885\u68ee\uff1a\u575a\u6301\u73b0\u5b9e\u4e3b\u4e49\u521b\u4f5c\u662f\u6211\u4e0d\u53d8\u7684\u6587\u5b66\u4fe1\u4ef0|date=21 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1970s, Zhou published his first work in ''[[Xinhua Daily]]''. A year later, he was transferred to Nanjing, working as an editor for ''Youth'', a recently-started magazine. He gained initial fame with his 1983 novella ''The Sinking Land'' ({{lang-zh|\u6c89\u6ca6\u7684\u571f\u5730}}),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2017-03/30/content_28731717.htm|title=Writer praised for anti-graft drama|website=China Daily}}{{dead link|date=January 2019}}</ref> then he became a professional writer since 1984. In the mid 1990s, he spent one year on secondment to a municipal government as deputy secretary general&nbsp;.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.infzm.com/content/122954|title=\"\u6211\u8ba4\u8bc6\u7684\u5f88\u591a\u5b98\u5458\u90fd'\u8fdb\u53bb'\u4e86\"  \u5468\u6885\u68ee\u7684\u653f\u6cbb\u5c0f\u8bf4\u65b0\u4f5c\u300a\u4eba\u6c11\u7684\u540d\u4e49\u300b|work=Southern Weekly}}</ref> In the meantime, he attempted to make a decent living by investing in business, stock and real estate.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=\u6211\u8981\u6811\u7acb\u81ea\u5df1\u7684\u54c1\u724c\u2014\u2014\u5468\u6885\u68ee\u8bbf\u8c08|url=|journal=\u5927\u4f17\u7535\u5f71|volume=2004|issue=4|pages=28\u201330}}</ref> The&nbsp;broad experience inspired him, and suffuses in his works.\n\nZhou's novels and scripts of the anti-graft dramas are in the public gaze. To make the plot vivid, he even visited a jail and interviewed the detained officials for corruption.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.cjn.cn/sywh/201704/t2994373.htm|title=\u5468\u6885\u68ee\uff1a\u300a\u4eba\u6c11\u7684\u540d\u4e49\u300b\u8fd9\u6761\u8239\u4e0a\u642d\u8f7d\u7684\u4e1c\u897f\u5f88\u591a|work=\u957f\u6c5f\u65e5\u62a5}}</ref>\n\nAs a major individual shareholder of some a listed&nbsp;company, Zhou published his open letters and called on individual investors against its reform of non-tradable shares to unite in 2005, since he claimed such a reform damages&nbsp;the&nbsp;interests&nbsp;of them. Eventually, the shareholders' meeting voted that down. The news caused a strong reaction among the individual investors, so he became the candidate for [[CCTV-2|CCTV]] Person of the Year for Social Common&nbsp;Good ({{lang-zh|\u793e\u4f1a\u516c\u76ca\u4eba\u7269}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/fortune/2005-12/06/content_3884017_22.htm|title=2005CCTV\u4e2d\u56fd\u7ecf\u6d4e\u5e74\u5ea6\u4eba\u726925\u4f4d\u5019\u9009\u4eba|website=Xinhua News}}{{dead link|date=January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''The Sinking Land''\n* ''Supreme Interest'' ({{lang-zh|\u81f3\u9ad8\u5229\u76ca}})\n* ''State Prosecution'' ({{lang-zh|\u56fd\u5bb6\u516c\u8bc9}})\n* ''[[In the Name of People|In the Name of the People]]''\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chinese novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Chinese novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Xuzhou]]\n[[Category:Chinese male novelists]]\n[[Category:Chinese television writers]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chinese male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Jiangsu]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhou_Meisen"}
